  "reasoning": "## 1) Key Findings\nAll 8 requested GPU targets were successfully probed; there were no failed or unsupported targets. Static/device attributes were stable across repeated runs: framebuffer bus width = 384 bits, max GPU frequency = 1,695,000 kHz, max memory frequency = 9,751,000 kHz, and SM count = 82. Profiled performance metrics reported: DRAM read throughput = 866,164,729,581.405 byte/second, DRAM write throughput = 789,058,697,068.31 byte/second, compute-memory throughput = 13.595% of peak sustained elapsed, and SM throughput = 82.22% of peak sustained elapsed.\n\n## 2) Confidence Caveats\nReported confidence is 0.95 for every target. Device attributes and SM count were repeated three times with identical values, indicating high consistency. Nsight Compute metrics came from generated benchmark kernels rather than direct built-in probes; although the final reported values are singular, underlying evidence shows multiple records for some metrics with wider raw ranges (for example, DRAM read and compute-memory throughput aggregates span multiple observations). DRAM write throughput was based on only one recorded metric sample, so it has less empirical redundancy than the other successful probes.\n\n## 3) Next Probes\nAdd sustained end-to-end bandwidth characterization under controlled kernels to relate the measured DRAM read/write rates to the 384-bit bus and max memory frequency. Probe achieved occupancy, active warps, and memory latency metrics to explain the gap between 13.595% memory-throughput utilization and 82.22% SM-throughput utilization. Capture per-kernel variance and repeat Nsight Compute collection for write bandwidth specifically, since that metric currently has only one recorded sample.",
